7. AI-Powered Self-Service: DataScout — The "Amazon-Like" Experience

Beyond building the Member DNA semantic layer, LatentView deployed DataScout, an AI-powered natural language query interface built on Databricks Genie, that sits on top of the Member DNA Gold layer and allows business users to interrogate member data by asking questions in plain English.

What DataScout Is:

A governed AI data room exposing 75 key member attributes through a conversational interface. The AI automatically:

Interprets the intent — understands what the user is asking, even with imprecise terminology
Generates optimized SQL — writes the correct query with filters, aggregations, groupings, and case logic
Executes and returns results — delivers tabular data with row counts
Auto-generates visualizations — produces charts appropriate to the data shape
Provides narrative summaries — explains the results in natural language
How DataScout Was Built:

DataScout was not a plug-and-play deployment — it required deliberate engineering to achieve production-grade accuracy.

Data Preparation — The 635+ column Member DNA table was decomposed into focused, denormalized analytical views and trimmed to 75 key attributes spanning demographics, enrollment, cost, risk, and health equity. Every column was annotated with business-friendly descriptions in Unity Catalog, authored jointly by LatentView engineers and Blue Shield SMEs.

Knowledge Store — A structured intelligence layer was built encoding Blue Shield's business logic: standardized SQL expressions for measures like PMPM and member months, filters like "active members" and "Medicare population," vetted example queries for the most common business questions, and prompt matching rules for abbreviations, misspellings, and date expressions like "last quarter." Synonyms ensured varied terminology across teams — "cost per head," "per-member cost," "PMPM" — all resolve correctly.

Benchmarking and Iteration — A benchmark suite of test questions with verified SQL answers was built and run regularly to track accuracy. Curation followed an iterative cycle: seed with minimal configuration, test with domain SMEs using Genie's built-in feedback system, review auto-suggested improvements from knowledge mining, and promote approved changes into the knowledge store.

Monitoring and Governance — Space managers review all user interactions via the Monitoring tab, triage flagged responses, and track adoption through audit logs. DataScout inherits Unity Catalog governance — access controls and data classification propagate automatically, keeping PHI protected even in a conversational interface.

